{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"014e3ced-f4ca-429a-b467-8bf2d2eddb6b","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these locations:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** (most common):\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_machinename.ips`. Recent crashes appear here within seconds.\n\n2. **Console.app** — Open it and navigate to **Crash Reports** in the sidebar for a GUI view of the same reports.\n\n3. **Core dumps** (if enabled):\n   ```bash\n   # Core dumps are disabled by default on macOS. To enable:\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   # Then reproduce the crash. The core file lands in /cores/\n   ls /cores/\n   ```\n   Note: on Apple Silicon, you may also need to disable SIP or sign the binary with the `com.apple.security.get-task-allow` entitlement for core dumps to be written.\n\n4. **system.log / unified log**:\n   ```bash\n   log show --predicate 'process == \"YourApp\"' --last 1h\n   ```\n\nThe `.ips` crash report in `DiagnosticReports` is usually the easiest starting point — it includes the exception type, faulting address, and a full thread backtrace.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"10b36d07-0f39-4f90-b81c-ea35af943cb2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT app on macOS when `createdump` isn't available. This is a general knowledge question - I don't need to search any codebase for this.","outputTokens":385,"requestId":"41A6:44010:60E2FB2:6A27D5F:69F1632C"},"id":"77cacd61-a505-4227-8a9b-9a3ec77aa990","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:47:36.028Z","parentId":"ec8f26dc-696d-469c-8a19-30a11187c9fa"}
